"Neelin J.D., Münnich M., Su H., Meyerson J.E., Holloway C.E.","Tropical drying trends in global warming models and observations",2006,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","103","16",,"6110","6115",,,10.1073/pnas.0601798103,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646555831&partnerID=40&md5=77884b895f382a214a90ce7838f0f4b6","Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90095, United States; Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States","Neelin, J.D., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90095, United States; Münnich, M., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90095, United States; Su, H., Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States; Meyerson, J.E., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90095, United States; Holloway, C.E., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90095, United States","Anthropogenic changes in tropical rainfall are evaluated in a multimodel ensemble of global warming simulations. Major discrepancies on the spatial distribution of these precipitation changes remain in the latest-generation models analyzed here. Despite this uncertainty, we find a number of measures, both global and local, on which reasonable agreement is obtained, notably for the regions of drying trend (negative precipitation anomalies). Models agree on the overall amplitude of the precipitation decreases that occur at the margins of the convective zones, with percent error bars of magnitude similar to those for the tropical warming. Similar agreement is found on a precipitation climate sensitivity defined here and on differential moisture increase inside and outside convection zones, a step in a hypothesized causal path leading to precipitation changes. A measure of local intermodel agreement on significant trends indicates consistent predictions for particular regions. Observed rainfall trends in several data sets show a significant summer drying trend in a main region of intermodel agreement: the Caribbean/Central-American region. © 2006 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Climate change; Drought; Tropical precipitation","article; Central America; climate; drought; greenhouse effect; model; moisture; observation; precipitation; prediction; priority journal; simulation; tropics; Caribbean Region; Central America; Greenhouse Effect; Human Activities; Models, Theoretical; Natural Disasters; Rain; Seasons; Tropical Climate",,,,,,"Roeckner, E., Bengtsson, L., Feichter, J., Lelieveld, J., Rodhe, H., (1999) J. Climate, 12, pp. 3004-3032; Hu, Z.-Z., Latif, M., Roeckner, E., Bengtsson, L., (2000) Geophys. Res. Lett., 27, pp. 2681-2684; Dai, A., Meehl, G.A., Washington, W.M., Wigley, T.M.L., Arblaster, J.M., (2001) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 82, pp. 2377-2388; Williams, K.D., Senior, C.A., Mitchell, J.F.B., (2001) J. Climate, 14, pp. 2659-2674; Yonetani, T., Gordon, H.B., (2001) J. Climate, 14, pp. 1765-1779; Douville, H., Chauvin, F., Planton, S., Royer, J.-F., Salas-Mélia, D., Tyteca, S., (2002) Climate Dyn., 20, pp. 45-68; Johns, T.C., Gregory, J.M., Ingram, W.J., Johnson, C.E., Jones, A., Lowe, J.A., Mitchell, J.F.B., Stevenson, D.S., (2003) Climate Dyn., 20, pp. 583-612; Manabe, S., Milly, P.C.D., Wetherald, R., (2004) Hydrol. Sci. J., 49, pp. 625-642; Allen, M.R., Ingram, W.J., (2002) Nature, 419, pp. 224-232; (2001) Climate Change, 2001, pp. 527-638. , Houghton, J. T., Ding, Y., Griggs, D. J., N